english:
  title: Memorial to the Respectful and Yielding King
  author: Yun Hoe-jong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    After the Profound Mausoleum passed beyond, powerful ministers like Yi In-im elevated the son of the rebel Sin-don, placing U upon the throne of our Wang dynasty. Thus the ancestral shrines fell silent for sixteen long years. Heaven's mercy has restored what seemed lost, and Your Highness must now think deeply and judge with clarity: present Sin-u and his father before the royal temple, then execute them in the marketplace. Only thus can you honor the spirits of nine generations, answer the wishes of your people, and seal the source of calamity.

    Consider: Guan Shu was elder brother, Duke of Zhou the younger. When Guan Shu conspired with Wu Geng and spread false rumors to incite rebellion, the Duke of Zhou executed him, and the royal house found peace. When Wang Mang usurped the throne, all under heaven yearned for Han. A man calling himself the son of Emperor Cheng appeared in Chang'an; Wang Mang had him killed. Later, a diviner named Wang Lang of Handan falsely claimed to be the true heir and declared himself emperor—hundreds of millions responded. Yet Emperor Guangwu, trapped at the Hu River and nearly devoured by starving tigers, prevailed only after this struggle, executing Wang Lang and restoring the imperial line.

    Cao Cao stole four centuries of Han's realm. When his son Cao Pi proclaimed himself emperor and changed the era name to rule the Central States, Zhuge Liang aided Liu Bei with these words: "Han and the usurper cannot both stand. Lead the three armies north to pacify the Central Plains, eliminate treachery, and restore the Han dynasty." His resolve was to bind Cao Pi's neck, report him at the temples of Gaozu and Guangwu, then execute him—thus to offer some measure of recompense to heaven.

    At that time, all the realm belonged to Wei, while Liu Bei held only a small corner in Shu. Yet when later historians recorded that era, they elevated Cao Pi as emperor. Only Zhu Xi, in compiling the Comprehensive Mirror, rejected Cao Pi's reign-name and instead recorded Liu Bei's era of Zhangwu, thus restoring the proper succession of Han.

    The Empress Wu of Tang deposed the Zhongzong Emperor, crowned herself, renamed the state Zhou, and sought to pass the realm to the Wu clan. Tang seemed lost. Zhang Jianzhi and others raised armies, restored Zhongzong's throne, executed Zhang Yizhi and Zhang Changsong, removed the Empress to Shangyang Palace, and restored the name Tang. Yet later virtuous scholars faulted them for failing to invoke righteousness against such extraordinary upheaval, to prosecute the criminals of the Tang house. They said: "Bring the Empress Wu before the Great Temple, enumerate her nine crimes, demote her to commoner status, grant her death, and extinguish her line, with Zhongzong taking no part in this—only thus would you comfort the spirits in heaven, assuage the people's grief, and establish the eternal order."

    When the two Zhangs fell, Xue Jichang, prefect of Luozhou, told Zhang Jianzhi: "Though the two villains are dead, Lusan still lives. Cut the grass but leave the root, and it will sprout again." Jianzhi replied: "The great matter is settled; they are but meat upon the board." Jichang sighed: "I know not where I shall die"—for the traitor Wu Sansi remained. Soon enough, Zhongzong and the Empress Wei placed trust in Wu Sansi again, and Zhang Jianzhi with five princes fell to his hand. The realm wept.

    Now Sin-u and his father usurped the throne for sixteen years, their relations and allies spread throughout the realm. Should ambitious villains gather to raise him again, I fear remorse will come too late and Your Highness's great work will be undone. The Duke of Zhou executed Guan Shu despite their kinship, for the realm's sake. Empress Wu, though Zhongzong's mother, is faulted by virtuous men for not being executed. How much more so for the descendants of treacherous ministers, who lack even such blood ties? Now that order is restored, what cause for hesitation? To spare them with stipends would only encourage further treachery. What of the sixteen years your ancestors endured without offerings? What of Jichang's warning about roots left uncut?

    Worldly upheaval arises from what we neglect and grows beyond our control. Can Your Highness afford not to ponder deeply for your realm's sake? Which minister in court does not wish to speak? They hold their tongues fearing their words will not be heeded, leaving only regret. As the classics say: "A ruler without secrecy loses his ministers; a minister without secrecy loses his life; schemes without secrecy fail." I humbly beseech that Your Highness confer with the great ministers in the inner palace, report Sin-u and his son before the Great Temple, execute them, and make this known throughout the realm. Thus prevent the royal house from being troubled again, spare the people further suffering, and ensure that the succession flows eternal to ten thousand generations.
  footnotes:
    - This memorial addresses the deposition of the usurper Sin-u (禑), who had been placed on the Korean throne after a period of political turmoil. Sin-u's position had just been reversed during what became known as the Reversal of Rectification (반정, Banjeong) in 1388.
    - The author employs historical precedents from Chinese history—the Duke of Zhou's execution of his brother Guan Shu, the handling of rebellions during the Han and Three Kingdoms periods, and the Empress Wu affair in Tang—to argue for the execution of the deposed ruler and his supporters.
    - The reference to 'sixteen years' marks the duration of Sin-u's usurpation and the interruption of proper sacrifices at the royal ancestral temples (nine generations = 구묘).
    - Zhu Xi (朱熹), known as Zhu Wenggong in Korean (주문공), was the great Neo-Confucian philosopher whose historical work, the Comprehensive Mirror for Aid in Governance (資治通鑑綱目), established precedent for judging historical legitimacy based on Confucian principles of righteousness rather than mere military or political control.
